You don't usually hear people raving about roasted chicken sandwiches but I am doing just that, but let me first get to the actual restaurant itself located in an unassuming building on a very busy road in Newton MA. After finding parking on the side of the road, I entered Cook and was instantly greeted by the hostess who asked if I was meeting someone, which I was, and was taken to my company immediately. While walking over to my seat, I noticed many people there, either sitting at the very nice wooden bar or sitting at small wooden tables with metal chairs, very modern/industrial design, along with the very high ceilings, all made for a very welcoming environment.  I was greeted by our server and we quickly each ordered the roasted chicken sandwich which had cranberry sage mayo, sweet onions, and fontina. The bread that the sandwich came on was toasted lightly and you could tell that they made the bread there in house, along with everything else, basically made from scratch. Each bite of the sandwich was better than the last and I truly enjoyed this lunch more than most I have had while working in Newton MA, and all for a great price as well, you do get what you pay for, so there's a bit of a premium but it is well worth it. I also had a Cucumber Basil Lemonata which was also fantastic.  The restaurant is only open for lunch from 11:30AM to 2:30PM so make sure you're not late to try some of the best lunch options in greater Boston at COOK in Newton MA, a fantastic option for a business meeting or to catch up with old friends or co-workers, you will not be disappointed, rather, pleasantly surprised.

It's very rare that a restaurant presents me with a dish that makes me say "wow." So when I have that happen twice in the same meal, it's something with noting. It's not that I'm picky, is just that once I read an ingredient list on the menu, I already begin to form a flavor profile in my mind. It's really only when a dish is able to truly transcend is ingredients that it truly wows me.  First, we had fries and charred broccoli for apps. The fries were nice and crisp and served with some nice dips (sriracha ketchup, a mustard of some sort, and a garlic herb aoli). The charred broccoli is literally a head of broccoli that's been roasted and topped with chimichurri. It's very different and really tasty for such a simple dish. The chimi is nice and fresh with a great mint flavor that nicely compliments the broccoli.  Then, we split the grilled cheese and sweet corn flatbread. I know what your thinking... Grilled cheese at a nice restaurant? Trust me... It's worth ordering and deserves it's place on the menu. Manchego and boursin combined with homemade pepper marmalade and a touch of honey mustard all combine on two slices of great bread to make a power-packed flavor explosion in your mouth. To top it off, there a side salad of field greens that's dressed lightly with some lemon vinaigrette that really is more than just a space filler or garnish... Such an excellent dish. The sweet corn flatbread was equally great. Mozzarella, boursin, sweet corn, bacon, and crispy kale make for a delectable flatbread that is truly different. It avoids harping on overplayed pizza/flatbread themes and is such a nice, clean, and balanced dish that is great for summer. The crispy kale especially adds such a nice texture and flavor to the dish. Overall, it's creamy, sweet, salty, and fresh... Truly a great dish.  If you haven't been here, I suggest rectifying that...I can't wait to go back!  ****UPDATE****  Due to our prior wonderful experience at Cook, we decided to return for another meal since we were in the neighborhood. We again ordered the grilled cheese and decided to try the chorizo flatbread. Honestly, had this been out first visit, we would not have returned. The grilled cheese was prepared such that the amounts of cheese and pepper jam were inconsistent from side to side, leaving part of the sandwich yummy while the other was distinctly "meh." Also, the previously wonderful field greens tasted unwashed and underdressed... Not worth even eating, honestly. The chorizo flatbread was also disappointing. It was so greasy that there was no real flavor, just a general greasy spice. The goat cheese was almost impossible to discern beyond a vague creaminess, which was really disappointing. Even the crust, which was great in the sweet corn flatbread of our last visit was laden with grease, rendering it soggy and flaccid. The final nail in the coffin was the lackluster service. The maitre d' honestly took better care of us then our waitress. Overall, a very disappointing experience. If recommend giving them a try on a weeknight, but it seems like weekend brunch has the B (or even C) team in the kitchen. It's sad when you get better food and service on a Monday evening twenty minutes prior to close then on a Saturday afternoon... I'm giving them a 4 star review based on the two-visit average, but even that is giving them the benefit of the doubt.

Went here last night with my wife and another couple. It's a bit closer to the suburbs than we typically find ourselves. That suburb location is apparent in the clientele (not that there is anything wrong with that). The other folks we went with had been there a couple times and only had great things to say. Cook did not disappoint.  Drinks:  Solid beer and wine selection, decent cocktail menu, would have appreciated more bourbon/whiskey based drinks, but the drinks we had were good - greta.  Food:  The group split the truffle fries for an app. They were everything you would dream of in fries; very crispy, nice amount of salt and flavoring, and a the right hint of truffle oil. Two of our group members are self proclaimed french fry connoisseurs and they both gave the fries 10/10.  Dinner, I got the NFC (Newton Fried Chicken), the biscuit was buttery and delicious (my friend order a side biscuit for his steak even), cole slaw tangy, and mashed potatoes solid. The chicken, the main, was great. Crispy, juicy and flavorful. Pro tip: dip the chicken in the gravy they give to you on the side.  My wife got the flatbread pizza that had Tuna on it. Freaking amazing, by far the best thing at the table. Basically they warm up a flat bread, put raw tuna, arugula, a spicy aioli and crispy shallots on top of it. Out of this world. HIGHLY recommended.  No room for desert, but I guess the brownie sundae is damn good as well.  TL;DR: Really good go here, order the truffle fries and the Tuna Flatbread, they are enough for 2 and freaking awesome.

I had the pportunity to visit this restaurant recently and was so pleasantly surprised.  The food, drinks and ambiance were superb.  It has the feel of a South End style place right here in Newton.  I had seen it from Washington St. and thought it looked kind of small, but it is so nicely decorated inside, it looks much bigger than it is.  I am a foodie and I can tell you the food was terrific.  The lobster sliders and the bolognese were out of this world!

This is one of my staple restaurants. Although, I haven't been as much recently since they removed their spinach salad from the menu. It was mixture of uncooked and slightly warmed spinach, cheese, a vinaigrette dressing, and some crostini type cranberry bread. However, the beers and wines are great, the pizzas amazing, and the bolognese is top notch! The burgers and other pasta dishes are also good, as is dessert. This place is always packed, but you can usually sit at the bar with no problem. The pizza oven is open to the restaurant and also has a bar built around it to sit at. The main bar is big and nice and then there are a bunch of tables and booths in the restaurant. It's intimate but still casual. The wait staff are all really friendly and helpful and the food is well priced!
